James de Villiers, News24Residents scratch through the rubble of destroyed homes in Mandela Park, Hout Bay. (Supplied) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town &ndash; One person was killed, 100 homes destroyed and 300 people displaced by a fire in Mandela Park, Hout Bay, on Sunday, the City of Cape Town said.&nbsp;This following fires in city on Saturday in which one person died, 100 homes were destroyed and 200 people were left homeless.&nbsp;These fires were in Mfuleni, Crossroads, &nbsp;Wallacedene, Lavender Hill, Gugulethu and New Rest Informal Settlement. Read:&nbsp;1 dead, over 200 displaced in Cape Town shack firesCity of Cape Town fire and rescue spokesperson Theo Layne said the city&rsquo;s fire department responded to a fire in Mandela Park, Hout Bay, at 02:15 on Sunday morning.&nbsp; The city&rsquo;s Informal Communities, Solid Waste, Water and Sanitation directorate has been deployed to Mandela Park to assist affected families, Layne said.&nbsp; The city&rsquo;s NGO partner Mustadafin Foundation were also on the scene to provide humanitarian relief.Layne said the cause of the blaze is undetermined at this stage.Layne said in a separate incident on Sunday a fire destroyed eight carriages and damaged three in Belmont Park Kraaifontein Railway station.&nbsp;Metrorail spokesperson Raina Scott could not be reached for comment.&nbsp;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.